english:
  title: Imperial Edict on the Pacification of Seogyeong by Commander-in-Chief Kim Busik and His Memorial
  author: Choe Ham
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I decree to you and others:

    I have received the memorial submitted by Lu Shu, Judge of the Left Army's Military Affairs, regarding the operations of the nineteenth day of the second month of this year. At dawn, he led troops silently into the rebel territory. The enemy forces scattered in defeat, unable to mount resistance. The false commander Choi Yeong was bound, and the corpse of the deputy commander Zhao Kuang was recovered. The rebels came forth together to surrender, and shortly thereafter the capital was entered, the palace swept clean, and the people both military and civilian comforted and pacified. I have learned all these details.

    I, possessed of meager virtue and dim understanding, hold place above the multitude of scholars and common folk. Yet I failed to restrain disorder before it arose, nor could I preserve the realm before peril came upon it. Recently, the insignificant people of the western capital conspired in great treachery, fabricating imperial decrees to mobilize troops and falsely establishing era names to deceive both heaven and earth. The circumstances were extraordinary and the crimes beyond forgiveness. Yielding to the collective counsel of my ministers in court, I commanded generals to march forth in punishment.

    You, undaunted by personal danger, resolutely accepted the mandate of command. You executed the treacherous ministers in the imperial capital and first eliminated those traitors working from within. You imposed strict discipline upon the army and perfected the strategy of coordinated assault. Though your aim was to annihilate the ringleaders, you did not slaughter the common followers who had no choice but to follow. First, you constructed great earthen mounds to break the rebels' will, casting massive stones to shatter their fortifications. Only then did you send forth the soldiers with disciplined silence to surge forward, whereupon the conspirators emerged with bound hands to surrender.

    You have swept away the malevolent influence and brought comfort to the elders and people. This has not only dispelled my nights of anxious toil, but also eased the grievances and frustrations of all within and without the realm. Had you not perceived the critical points of safety and danger, not understood the proper sequence of swift and measured action, how could you have achieved such complete subjugation of the fierce rebels without costly warfare? Though the initial campaign required a full year, its completion came in a single dawn.

    In ancient times, the High Ancestor of the Yin Dynasty and the Duke of Zhou each required three years to pacify their rebellions, yet their achievements were celebrated for ten thousand generations. How much more glorious is this present deed—truly a beacon to illuminate the histories!

    I have already sent intimate courtiers to convey special commendation, and now seeing your memorial of thanksgiving and your gracious deflection of praise to the throne, I am moved to endless admiration. Therefore I issue this edict for your full understanding. As spring warmth arrives, may you and all enjoy peace and ease. My brush cannot express all that fills my heart.
  footnotes:
    - The 'western capital' (Seogyeong) refers to Pyeongyang, site of a rebellion in 1135 during the Goryeo dynasty. Commander-in-Chief Kim Busik successfully suppressed this uprising.
    - The reference to the 'High Ancestor of the Yin Dynasty' and 'Duke of Zhou' invokes classical precedents of virtuous military campaigns that took considerable time but were remembered for their righteousness and effectiveness.
